 ],
 "text": "For most of its history, China wrote in a language that almost nobody actually spoke. You'd say something out loud, and then write it down in a completely different language. Same meaning, but different words, and different grammar. Here's how that happened. The written language was called Wenyanwen, classical Chinese, and it was based on the way people spoke more than 2,000 years ago. Then it basically froze. Scholars kept writing in that same ancient style century after century, but the spoken language never stopped changing. Take a simple, everyday word, like the word for you. Over the centuries, the way people said it slowly shifted, but to write it, you were still expected to use the ancient form. Do that across the whole language, and the Chinese people spoke, and the Chinese they wrote drifted into two different worlds, one alive and changing, the other frozen in time. Linguists have a name for this, Deglossia. One language for talking, another for writing, and it made being literate brutally hard. You didn't just have to learn the characters. You had to master what was almost a dead language, on top of the one you already spoke, so reading and writing stayed locked to a small, educated elite. For everyone else, the way they actually talked just wasn't considered proper to write down. Then, around 1917, a scholar named Hu Shi pushed a radical idea, simply write the way you speak. Use the living, spoken language, baihua, as the written standard, and it caught on fast. Within about a decade, schools and newspapers had traded classical Chinese for the language people actually used. So for two thousand years, China wrote in a language that time had left behind, and it took a 20th century revolution just to let people write the way they talk. We take it for granted that we write our own language. For most of Chinese history, that simply wasn't allowed. Want to actually start learning Chinese? Discover thousands of free exercises and more learning content on stacktags.io."
